## Phone Catalogue App.

The objective with this app is to display detailed information for a phone when the user clicks it on the main view - see example below:

![][detail3]

The URL for the new view is __parameterized__, for example:

>'http://localhost:3000/phones/droid-2-global-by-motorola', where *droid-2-global-by-motorola* is a phone identifier. 

The general form of the URL is:

>http://localhost:3000/phones/:id

For convenience, all phone specifications are stored in JSON files at `phoneCatalogue/public/phoneSpecs/phones`. For example, the file pathname for the sample phone mentioned above is: `phoneCatalogue/public/phoneSpecs/phones/droid-2-global-by-motorola.json`. Find it in your filesystem.

### Setup.

From `threeApps/phoneCatalogue` folder, install the React Router package:

       $ npm install react-router-dom@4.2.2 --save

and also the Superagent packages:

      $ npm install  superagent@1.6.1 --save

Start the development server:

      $ npm start 

### Routing Requirements.

This app will support two URL routes:

1. The root path (/) - Display the main view (already developed).
1. /phones/:id - Display a detailed specification for a specific phone.

### Routing implementation.

In `phoneCatalogue/src/index.js`, replace the entire content with the following:

    import React, { Component } from 'react';
    import ReactDOM from 'react-dom';
    import { BrowserRouter, Route, Redirect, Switch } from 'react-router-dom';
    import App from './App';
    import '../node_modules/bootstrap/dist/css/bootstrap.css';
    import PhoneDetail from './components/phoneDetail'

     class Router extends Component {    //}= (props) => 
        render() {  
           return ( 
            <BrowserRouter>
                <div className="jumbotron">
                   <div className="container-fluid">
                      <div className="row">
                          <div className="col-md-10" >
                            <h1>Phone Catalogue App</h1>
                          </div>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                    <Switch>
                        <Route path='/phones/:id' component={ PhoneDetail } />
                        <Route exact path='/' component={ App } />
                        <Redirect from='*' to='/' />
                    </Switch>
                </div>
            </BrowserRouter>
      );
     }
    }

    ReactDOM.render(<Router />, document.getElementById('root'));

[This change causes some errors, which can be ignored for the moment.]

Some points to note in the above code:

1. The last import statement refers to the components that will render the phone specification page - developed below.
1. The app's routing logic is declared in a separate component, Router. It is the component passed to  ReactDOM.render().
1. The routing component includes some __static/persistent elements__. They representing the fixed header across all views in the app.

The App component should no longer displays a header. In `src/App.js` reduce the render method return statement to the following:

        return (
            <div className="row">
                <SelectControls onUserInput={this.handleChange } 
                    filterText={this.state.search} 
                    sort={this.state.sort} />
                <PhoneList phones={filteredList} />
            </div> 
        );


Create the file `src/components/phoneDetail/index.js`. The new *PhoneDetail* component (and its children) will need a significant amount of code, however, we will use a stub implementation for starters; add the following code to the new file:

      import React, {Component} from 'react';
      import { withRouter } from 'react-router-dom';

      class PhoneDetail extends Component {
        render() {
          return (
              <div className="container-fluid">
                <div className="row">
                  <div className="col-md-10">
                    <h3> Phone id: {this.props.match.params.id} </h3>
                    <h3> Detail page stub </h3>
                  </div>    
                </div>
            </div>
            );
        }
      };

        export default withRouter(PhoneDetail);

The main feature to note here is how the component accesses the parameter portion of the active URL address (a phone id). The *withRouter()* function injects various routing-related props in to the component, including the *this.props.match.params* object.  

In the browser the main view should now be rendering correctly. Click any phone on the page to see the new stub view - see example below:

![][detail1]

This demonstrates the hyperlinks on the main view do work, however they are 'external' links - they are not integrated in to the React Router system. To fix this we must replace the HTML anchor tags with the React Router __Link__ tag/component. We will also taken the opportunity to use React's stateless function component style. In `src/components/phone/index.js`, replace the entire content with the following::

      import React from 'react';
      import './phone.css';
      import { Link } from 'react-router-dom';

      const Phone = ( props ) => {
              const { id, imageUrl, name, snippet } = props.phone
              const fullImageURL = `phoneSpecs/${imageUrl}`
              const path = `/phones/${id}`
              return (
                  <li className="thumbnail phone_item">
                      <Link to={path} className="thumb">
                          <img src={fullImageURL} alt={name} /> 
                      </Link>
                      <Link to={path}> {name}</Link>
                      <p>{snippet}</p>
                  </li>
              ) ;
      }

      export default Phone

In the browser, go to the main view and click some phone links. Notice the URL in the address bar changes. A sample URL might be:

>>http://localhost:3000/phones/motorola-bravo-with-motoblur 

### The PhoneDetail component. 

Phone details are stored in JSON files, for example, see `phoneCatalogue/public/phoneSpecs/specs/dell-streak-7.json`. Our React app can access this data using a HTTP GET request to the development server. In `components/phoneDetail/index.js`, update the code as follows:

    . . . . other imports . . . . 
    import localCache from '../../localCache';
    import request from 'superagent' ; 

    class PhoneDetail extends Component {
        componentDidMount() {
            const url = `/phoneSpecs/phones/${this.props.match.params.id}.json`
            request.get( url, 
                (err, res) => {
                  let json = JSON.parse(res.text);
                  localCache.setPhone(json);
                  this.setState({});
                }) ;
        } 

        render(){
            let display = <p>No phone details</p> ; 
            let phone = localCache.getPhone();
            if (phone) {
                display =  
                  <div>
                      <h2>{phone.name} </h2>
                      <p>{phone.description}</p>
                  </div> 
            }
            return (
                <div className="container-fluid">
                  <div className="row">
                      <div className="col-md-10">
                          {display}
                      </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
            );
        }
        export default withRouter(PhoneDetail);


Ignore any errors this produces for the moment. This code uses a simple custom class to cache the current phone being viewed. Create the file `src/localCache.js` and paste in the following:

      class LocalCache {
          constructor() {
              this.phone = null 
          }

          setPhone(phone) {
              this.phone = phone 
          }

          getPhone() {
              return this.phone
          }

      }
      export default (new LocalCache() );

In the PhoneDetail component the *componentDidMount* method uses the Superagent library to make the HTTP request. The asynchronous nature of this behavior means we need to force a re-rendering after a response is received. The built-in setState() method achieves this, even though the component has no actual state data. 

In the browser, click any phone in the main page to test the new code.

We will delegate the content for this view to two new components, as illustrated below:

